<br>
Background.  On October 16th we got a new owner.  We are no longer a &quot;corporate store&quot;.  We have an owner who happens to own the 28 other previously &quot;corporate&quot; stores.  We do not have a machine to run checks through.  I have no way to tell if a check is good or not, except by calling the bank <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>if</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they are open.  I have been told that we can accept checks from regular customers.  All of my employees have worked there for less than a month.  How do they know who the regulars are?  So we have signs up on the pumps, on the front door, everywhere saying that we no longer accept checks.<br>
<br>
IT'S NOT MY FAULT YOU CAN'T READ THE SIGNS BEFORE YOU BOUGHT YOUR FUEL.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry to inconvenience you.  I wish I could accept your check in good faith.  Unfortunately I've been doing this for way too long, and I don't trust anyone anymore except the customers I know by name.  And I would say that none of the cashiers have a freaking clue.<br>
<br>
So why would threatening to get your neighborhood boycotting my store fix anything?  I have been waiting for a money order machine, and a check service since October 16th.  I took a pay cut to keep my job.  I won't be eligable for paid vacation for over a year.  My first paycheck was delayed by over a week.  I have just as much fun with the new system as you the customer do.  I'm sorry, I really am, but I'm already tearing my hair out.  GET OVER IT.<br>
<br>
Thank you, have a great day, and come see us again when you decide that you really need gas at our store again cause it's convenient.  Cause I know you will.  I've seen it happen.<br>
<br>
